---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import LessonShell from "../../components/LessonShell.astro";
import FakeTerminal from "../../components/FakeTerminal.astro";
import Reveal from "../../components/Reveal.astro";
import { LESSONS } from "../../data/curriculum";

const lesson = LESSONS.find((l) => l.id === "code-slash")!;
---

<Layout title={`${lesson.title} · Learn Claude`}>
  <main>
    <LessonShell lesson={lesson}>
      <p>
        Below is a faithful imitation of Claude Code. It streams output the same way,
        uses the same slash menu (arrow keys + Enter), and shows the same
        "Claude wants to do this — Allow / Deny" approval prompts before touching your machine.
        Drive it like you would the real CLI.
      </p>

      <FakeTerminal cwd="~/my-project" />

      <h2>Things to try</h2>
      <ol class="steps">
        <li>Press <kbd>/</kbd> and use <kbd>↑</kbd>/<kbd>↓</kbd> + <kbd>Enter</kbd> to pick a command. Try <code class="inline">/agents</code>.</li>
        <li>Type "<em>fix the bug</em>" — Claude reads files, runs your tests, finds the cause.</li>
        <li>Type "<em>add a dark mode toggle</em>" — you'll get an Allow/Deny prompt before any file is written.</li>
        <li>Type "<em>list files</em>" — note the tool call is visible (the "● Listing your project files" line).</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Slash commands worth knowing on day one</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><code class="inline">/help</code> — what I can do.</li>
        <li><code class="inline">/clear</code> — start a fresh chat (keeps your project context).</li>
        <li><code class="inline">/plan</code> — plan mode: Claude outlines steps before touching files.</li>
        <li><code class="inline">/agents</code> — list specialized assistants.</li>
        <li><code class="inline">/model</code> — switch Sonnet/Opus/Haiku.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Agents: specialized helpers</h2>
      <p>An <strong>agent</strong> is a focused version of Claude — same model, but with a job description and only the tools it needs. Examples:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>code-reviewer</strong> — reads a diff and reports bugs, smells, missing tests.</li>
        <li><strong>tdd-guide</strong> — enforces "write the test first" when you're adding a feature.</li>
        <li><strong>build-error-resolver</strong> — narrows in on a failing build and fixes only what's needed.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>You don't usually call them directly — Claude reaches for them when the work matches.</p>

      <h2>Skills</h2>
      <p>A <strong>skill</strong> is a reusable recipe (Markdown + maybe a script) for "how we do X here". A skill called <em>hotel-research</em> tells Claude exactly how to research hotels for you: which sites to check, what to summarize, what to skip. Skills live in <code class="inline">~/.claude/skills/</code>; you can write your own.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <strong>Slash command vs agent vs skill — quick map.</strong>
        <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0 0;">
          <li><strong>Slash command:</strong> "do this <em>action</em> now" (clear chat, change model).</li>
          <li><strong>Agent:</strong> "switch to this <em>persona</em> for the next bit of work".</li>
          <li><strong>Skill:</strong> "use this <em>recipe</em> whenever the situation matches".</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <Reveal q="What's the deal with Allow / Deny?">
        Claude Code never silently modifies your machine. Anything that reads, writes, or runs a command
        asks first. You can grant standing permission for trusted operations.
      </Reveal>
    </LessonShell>
  </main>
</Layout>
